Here's an example of a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

int main() {
    // Declare variables
    string word;
    int count;
    ifstream inputFile;
    // Open the file
    inputFile.open("file.txt");
    // Check if the file could be opened
    if (!inputFile) {
        cerr << "Could not open file" << endl;
        return 1;
    }
    // Read first line
    getline(inputFile, word);
    // Count occurrences of word
    while (getline(inputFile, word)) {
        count++;
    }
    // Close the file
    inputFile.close();
    // Display the result
    cout << "Number of occurrences of " << word << " in file "
         << "\"file.txt\" is " << count << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This program reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file. The program receives the input for the word to be counted from the user and opens the text file. If the file could not be opened, the program prints an error message and exits with a non-zero exit code.

Once the file is opened, the program reads the first line of the file and stores it in the `word` variable. This line of the file contains the word to be counted. After reading the first line, the program enters a loop that reads each line of the file and counts the number of occurrences of the word in that line. The loop continues until the end of the file is reached or a blank line is found.

Once the loop has finished, the program displays the result, which is the total number of occurrences of the word in the text file. Finally, the program closes the file and exits.

This program can be modified to count the occurrences of multiple words or to read the file from a command line argument instead of from a file path.

